\textbf{Based on the following knowledge:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item An isosceles triangle is a triangle with two equal interior angles, and the sides opposite these angles are also equal.
    \item A right triangle is a triangle with one interior angle of 90 degrees.
    \item The sum of the interior angles of a triangle is 180 degrees.
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Without using methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations, prove that:}
The length of the median to the hypotenuse of a right triangle is half the length of the hypotenuse.

\textbf{Given a triangle \(ABC\), based on the following knowledge:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item If two lines are parallel, the alternate interior angles are equal.
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Prove that the sum of the interior angles of triangle \(ABC\) is \(180\) degrees.}

\textbf{Based on the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item If two lines in a plane do not intersect, they are called parallel lines.
    \item Through a point outside a line, there is exactly one line parallel to the given line.
\end{enumerate}
\textbf{Prove that:}

If two lines are each parallel to a third line, then they are parallel to each other.

\textbf{Using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item The Pythagorean theorem.
    \item The criteria for triangle congruence.
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Prove that:}
If the sides of a triangle \(a\), \(b\), and \(c\) satisfy the relationship \(a^2 + b^2 = c^2\), then the triangle is a right triangle.

In square \(ABCD\), \(M\) and \(N\) are moving points on \(BC\) and \(CD\) respectively, and \(\angle MAN = 45^\circ\). The diagonal \(BD\) intersects \(AM\) and \(AN\) at points \(E\) and \(F\) respectively.

\textbf{Using only the following properties:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties of a square.
    \item The criteria and properties of congruent triangles.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove:}
\(MN = BM + DN\)

\textbf{Given a rectangle \(ABCD\) with points \(A\), \(B\), \(C\), and \(D\) arranged counterclockwise and \(AD\) above \(BC\). \(AB = n\) and \(BC = m\). Point \(P\) is a moving point on segment \(BC\), and point \(M\) is a point on segment \(AP\) such that \(\angle ADM = \angle BAP\).}

\textbf{Using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Properties of circles.
    \item The triangle inequality.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove that \(BM \geq \sqrt{\left(\frac{m}{2}\right)^2 + n^2} - \frac{m}{2}\).}

\textbf{In square \(ABCD\), \(M\) and \(N\) are moving points on \(BC\) and \(CD\) respectively, and \(\angle MAN = 45^\circ\). The diagonal \(BD\) intersects \(AM\) and \(AN\) at points \(E\) and \(F\) respectively.}

\textbf{Using only the following properties:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties of a square.
    \item The criteria and properties of congruent triangles.
    \item The properties of right triangles.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove:} \(EF^2 = BE^2 + DF^2\)

\textbf{Given a square \(ABCD\) with side length \(a\), points \(E\) and \(F\) are on sides \(BC\) and \(CD\) respectively, and \(\angle EAF = 45^\circ\). If \(EP \perp AC\) and \(FQ \perp AC\),}

\textbf{Using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The criteria and properties of similar triangles.
    \item The properties of a square.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system, parametric equations, or vectors.}

\textbf{Prove that \(AP \cdot AQ\) is a constant value.}

\textbf{In square \(ABCD\), \(M\) and \(N\) are moving points on \(BC\) and \(CD\) respectively, and \(\angle MAN = 45^\circ\). The diagonal \(BD\) intersects \(AM\) and \(AN\) at points \(E\) and \(F\) respectively.}

\textbf{Using only the following properties:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties of a square.
    \item The criteria and properties of congruent triangles.
    \item The properties of right triangles.
    \item The criteria and properties of similar triangles.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove:} \(\triangle AEF \sim \triangle ANM\)

\textbf{In square \(ABCD\), \(M\) and \(N\) are moving points on \(BC\) and \(CD\) respectively, and \(\angle MAN = 45^\circ\). The diagonal \(BD\) intersects \(AM\) and \(AN\) at points \(E\) and \(F\) respectively.}

\textbf{Using only the following properties:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties of a square.
    \item The criteria and properties of congruent triangles.
    \item The properties of right triangles.
    \item The criteria and properties of similar triangles.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove:} \(\triangle AEN\) is an isosceles right triangle.

\textbf{Given that \(AB\) is the diameter of circle \(\odot O\), points \(C\) and \(D\) are moving points on \(\odot O\) (both points are on opposite sides of \(AB\) and do not coincide with \(A\) or \(B\)). Connect \(CD\) to intersect \(AB\) at point \(E\), and connect \(AC\) and \(BC\). If \(OA = r\) and \(\angle DCB = 60^\circ\), and for any point \(C\), there exists a point \(F\) on chord \(CD\) such that \(BC = 2DF\), connect \(BF\).}

\textbf{Using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties and criteria for similar triangles.
    \item The properties of circles.
    \item The properties of right triangles.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system.}

\textbf{Prove that \(BF \geq \frac{\sqrt{13} - 1}{2} r\).}

\textbf{In an acute triangle \(\triangle ABC\) with points \(A\), \(B\), and \(C\) arranged counterclockwise and \(A\) above \(BC\), \(\angle A = 60^\circ\). Points \(D\) and \(E\) are moving points on sides \(AB\) and \(AC\) respectively, and \(BE\) intersects line \(CD\) at point \(F\).}

\textbf{If \(AB = AC\) and \(BD = AE\), rotate segment \(AC\) clockwise around point \(C\) by \(60^\circ\) to obtain segment \(CM\), and connect \(MF\). Point \(N\) is the midpoint of \(MF\), and connect \(CN\). During the movement of points \(D\) and \(E\), using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The criteria and properties of congruent triangles.
    \item The properties of parallel lines.
    \item The criteria and properties of parallelograms.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove that \(BF + CF = 2CN\).}

\textbf{In \(\triangle ABC\), \(AB = AC\), \(AD \perp BC\), \(CG \parallel AB\), and \(BG\) intersects \(AD\) and \(AC\) at \(E\) and \(F\) respectively.}

\textbf{Using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties and criteria for similar triangles.
    \item The properties of isosceles triangles.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove that \(\frac{EF}{BE} \cdot \frac{GE}{BE} = 1\).}

\textbf{In \(\triangle ABC\), \(\angle ACB = 90^\circ\), point \(D\) is inside \(\triangle ABC\). Connect \(BD\) and \(DC\), and extend \(DC\) to point \(E\) such that \(CE = DC\). Connect \(AE\) and intersect the extension of \(BD\) at point \(H\), and connect \(CH\). If \(AB^2 = AE^2 + BD^2\),}

\textbf{Using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties of right triangles.
    \item The properties of parallelograms.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove that \(CD = CH\).}

\textbf{In \(Rt \triangle ABC\) with \(\angle C = 90^\circ\), \(AC = m\), and \(BC = n\), a circle is drawn with center \(A\) and radius \(r\) (\(r < m\)). Point \(D\) is a moving point on \(BC\), and two tangents are drawn from \(D\) to \(\odot A\), touching the circle at points \(E\) and \(F\). Connect \(EF\), and let point \(G\) be the midpoint of \(EF\).}

\textbf{Using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties of circles.
    \item The properties of similar triangles.
    \item The Pythagorean theorem.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove that \(BG \geq \sqrt{\left(m - \frac{r^2}{2m}\right)^2 + n^2} - \frac{r^2}{2m}\).}

\textbf{In rhombus \(ABCD\) with points \(A\), \(B\), \(C\), and \(D\) arranged counterclockwise and \(AD\) above \(BC\), \(\angle ABC = 60^\circ\) and \(AB = l\). Point \(P\) is a moving point on line \(AD\), and point \(E\) is on ray \(BP\) such that \(\angle BEC = \angle BCP\).}

\textbf{Using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties and criteria for similar triangles.
    \item The properties of a rhombus.
    \item The properties of circles.
    \item The triangle inequality.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove that \(CE \geq \frac{l}{\sqrt{3}}\).}

\textbf{Point \(D\) is a point inside an equilateral \(\triangle ABC\). If \(\angle BDC = 120^\circ\),}

\textbf{Using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties and criteria for similar triangles.
    \item The properties of parallel lines.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Prove that \(\frac{DA}{DB} \geq \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\).}

\textbf{In \(\triangle ABC\), \(\angle ACB = 90^\circ\), \(\angle BAC = \alpha\), and \(AB = l\). If point \(P\) is a point inside \(\triangle ABC\), using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties and criteria for congruent triangles.
    \item The properties of isosceles, equilateral, and right triangles.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove that \(PA + PB + PC \geq l \sqrt{1 + \sqrt{3} \sin(\alpha) \cos(\alpha)}\).}

\textbf{In \(\triangle ABC\), \(\angle C = 90^\circ\). The angle bisectors of \(\angle A\) and \(\angle B\), \(AD\) and \(BE\), intersect \(BC\) and \(AC\) at points \(D\) and \(E\) respectively. \(AD\) and \(BE\) intersect at point \(I\). Given that the area of \(\triangle ABI\) is \(S\).}

\textbf{Using only the following knowledge:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The properties and criteria for congruent triangles.
    \item The method of calculating the area of a triangle.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Without using advanced methods such as establishing a coordinate system or parametric equations.}

\textbf{Prove that the area of quadrilateral \(ABDE\) is \(2S\).}
